== History ==
The exact origins of the shrine are unknown. Records from the {{ill|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|ja|日本文徳天皇実録|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft}} suggest that rituals were being conducted at the shrine during the early [[Heian period]]. It is listed among the eight shrines of [[Hida Province]] in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Kenmu|ja|建武|12=draft}} era, the local lord {{ill|Ema Clan|ja|江馬氏|12=draft}} invited a divided spirit of the {{ill|Suwa Daimyōjin|ja|諏訪大明神|12=draft}}, changing the shrine's name to Suwa Daimyōjin. Following periods of rule by the Ema, {{ill|Miki Clan|ja|三木氏|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kanamori Clan|ja|金森氏|12=draft}}, the shrine's original name was restored in 1804 after extensive research by followers of {{ill|Tanaka Ōhide|ja|田中大秀|12=draft}}.

In 1871, under the {{ill|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft}}, Ōtsu Shrine was designated a prefectural shrine. In 1930, it was elevated to special {{ill|Kinpei-sha|ja|金幣社|12=draft}} status.

== Grounds ==
* Main Shrine
* Auxiliary Shrines
* Handwashing Basin
* First Torii Gate (completed in 1928)
* Second Torii Gate

