== History ==
The exact origins of the shrine are unknown. Records from the {{ill|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|ja|日本文徳天皇実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|qq=}} and the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}} suggest that rituals were being conducted at the shrine during the early [[Heian period]]. It is listed among the eight shrines of [[Hida Province]] in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Kenmu|ja|建武|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenmu|qq=}} era, the local lord {{ill|Ema Clan|ja|江馬氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ema Clan|qq=}} invited a divided spirit of the {{ill|Suwa Daimyōjin|ja|諏訪大明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Daimyōjin|qq=}}, changing the shrine's name to Suwa Daimyōjin. Following periods of rule by the Ema, {{ill|Miki Clan|ja|三木氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miki Clan|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kanamori Clan|ja|金森氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanamori Clan|qq=}}, the shrine's original name was restored in 1804 after extensive research by followers of {{ill|Tanaka Ōhide|ja|田中大秀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanaka Ōhide|qq=}}.

In 1871, under the {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}}, Ōtsu Shrine was designated a prefectural shrine. In 1930, it was elevated to special {{ill|Kinpei-sha|ja|金幣社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinpei-sha|qq=}} status.

