''' {{ill|Kukunochi no Kami|ja|久久能智大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kukunochi no Kami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}

== History ==
The exact origins of the shrine are unknown. Records from the [[:en:Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku]] and the [[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]] suggest that rituals were being conducted at the shrine during the early [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. It is listed among the eight shrines of [[:en:Hida Province|Hida Province]] in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=}}.

During the [[:en:Jianwu|Kenmu]] era, the local lord {{ill|Ema Clan|ja|江馬氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ema Clan|qq=}} invited a divided spirit of the {{ill|Suwa Daimyōjin|ja|諏訪大明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Daimyōjin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 諏訪神社}}, changing the shrine's name to Suwa Daimyōjin. Following periods of rule by the Ema, {{ill|Miki Clan|ja|三木氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miki Clan|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kanamori Clan|ja|金森氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanamori Clan|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, the shrine's original name was restored in 1804 after extensive research by followers of [[:en:Tanaka Ōhide|Tanaka Ōhide]].

In 1871, under the [[:en:Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]], Ōtsu Shrine was designated a prefectural shrine. In 1930, it was elevated to special {{ill|Kinpei-sha|ja|金幣社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinpei-sha|qq=}} status.

== Grounds ==
* Main Shrine
* Auxiliary Shrines
* Handwashing Basin
* First Torii Gate (completed in 1928)
* Second Torii Gate

